&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;/div&gt;






&lt;h3&gt;


When this isn't a good fit
&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This approach is developer-centric by design, so, if your workflow relies on:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;external translators&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;"Crowdin" / "Lokalise" / similar tools&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;non-technical editors touching translation files&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;you have A LOT of supported languages&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;then this probably isn't the right approach.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;But, if translations are written and maintained in code, and your supported language set is small-to-medium, the DX ends up being surprisingly nice.&lt;/p&gt;




&lt;p&gt;If you're curious, the project is open source. You can check it out:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;a href="https://github.com/akocan98/react-scoped-i18n" rel="noopener noreferrer"&gt;GitHub&lt;/a&gt;: &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/react-scoped-i18n" rel="noopener noreferrer"&gt;npm&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Happy to hear any feedback!&lt;/p&gt;

